The genome of the SARS coronavirus encodes two large replicase polyproteins (replicase polyproteins) ppla (486 kDa) and pplab (790 kDa), these two proteins are encoded by the genome of 2/3 to 3/4 of the coronavirus. These two proteins are hydrolyzed to produce many functional subunits of the viral replication complex. In this hydrolysis process, the main proteolytic enzyme of SARS coronavirus (main protease, abbreviated as M pro , molecular weight 33.8 kDa, sometimes called 3C-Like Protein) plays a very important role. The main protease is also a segment of ppla and pplab, its release is achieved by autocatalytic hydrolysis, and autocatalytic hydrolysis occurs at the Gln S er , Al a ) site beside the protease, by trans-splicing (bi-molecular reaction) carry out. Under the action of the main protease, the replicase polyproteins ppla and pplab are hydrolyzed into more than a dozen functional peptides, which further play a role. If it can inhibit the hydrolysis of SARS coronavirus main protease, it will effectively resist the infection of SARS coronavirus. Therefore, SARS coronavirus primary protease is an ideal target for anti-SARS drug design. Summary of invention
